    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2164687237" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2164687237" />
    <a title="Jill" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2228181-jill"><img alt="Jill" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1507660688p2/2228181.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2164687237?book_show_action=true">Oct 31, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jill" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jill" href="/user/show/2228181-jill">Jill</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2164687237" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9432163485322505735">Right from the start, we know how this novel will end: with all six bedrooms of the Richardson house set ablaze, likely by Izzy, the youngest and most free-spirited of the Richardson children. And, of course, we also know the symbolism of the fire: burn the prevailing constrictions and self-absorption to the ground.<br/><br/>The core conflict of the story is between Mrs. Richardson, a rules follower who has embodies the life we’re all told to strive for: college, marriage, kids, and becoming a pillar of s</span>
  <span id="freeText9432163485322505735" style="display:none">Right from the start, we know how this novel will end: with all six bedrooms of the Richardson house set ablaze, likely by Izzy, the youngest and most free-spirited of the Richardson children. And, of course, we also know the symbolism of the fire: burn the prevailing constrictions and self-absorption to the ground.<br /><br />The core conflict of the story is between Mrs. Richardson, a rules follower who has embodies the life we’re all told to strive for: college, marriage, kids, and becoming a pillar of society. She is contrasted with Mia, a devil-may-care visual artist and single mom who rents a house from the Richardsons with her studious teenager, Pearl. Eventually, lines are drawn when a co-worker of Mia’s is forced to abandon her infant Chinese daughter, and friends of the Richardsons, who are white, privileged, and desperate for their own child, take her in and raise her as their own.<br /><br />As a character-driven reader, I felt that this tightly plotted novel, while enjoyable, strained at credibility and sacrificed character development for plot. There is no way for me to write this review without spoilers, so if you haven’t yet read it, STOP RIGHT HERE – SPOILER ALERT.<br /><br />First, we are led to believe that a wealthy man stalks a young Mia and propositions her to bear the child that he and his barren wife have long wanted. The reason is that Mia looks amazingly like his wife Okay—huh? Here is a couple who can easily afford a surrogate and instead, turn to an unknown girl who the husband happens to run across and who has not been thoroughly vetted by them. And children are rarely mirror-images of their parents.<br /><br />Does Mia run for the hills? Absolutely not. She needs money for school and she rather quickly agrees to move forward with this. There is very little introspection; they are “nice people” so “why not?” Then, she changes her mind because of a family death – again, quickly and without introspection.<br /><br />Mrs. Richardson, who is a sometime-journalist, decides to suddenly revive her passion for investigative reporting and investigates Mia’s past because she believes Mia is responsible for the emotional turmoil that her friends her in. She tracks down Mia’s parents, and after years of silence, they suddenly feel compelled to share the story with this journalist-stranger. <br /><br />Oh, and in one particularly egregious passage, the would-be adopted mother of the Chinese baby (this subplot shows how history repeats itself) is so clueless that on the stand, when asked how she would teach the baby about her culture, searches her brain and says, “Well, we go to Chinese restaurants.” This is so dumbed-down as to be unbelievable.<br /><br />And then there’s the Richardson kids. Every stereotype in the world is employed here: the good-looking jock brother, the pretty teen and her black boyfriend (“No one sees race here”) who get “into trouble”, the rebellious younger daughter – and, of curse, the blatant clash between rule followers and free spirits, the haves and the have nots.<br /><br />Last year, I read a book entitled Lucky Boy by Shanthi Sekaran. It’s a heart-wrenching and nuanced book that pick sup some of these same themes and does so in a most believable and non-manipulative way. THAT is the book I recommend.<br /> <br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="9432163485322505735" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


