<div id="review_2366481232" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2366481232" />
    <a title="David Putnam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5463364-david-putnam"><img alt="David Putnam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1372638034p2/5463364.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2366481232?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Putnam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Putnam" href="/user/show/5463364-david-putnam">David Putnam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2366481232" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7087005253423983546">DNF This is a great book, just not for me. The author is brilliant in her craft. As I have said before I am big on the Fictive Dream, have to have it. This book is a study in character. There is so much “telling” about the characters that the narrative overpowers the forward motion of the story. There isn’t any forward motion of the story that I could see in the first hundred pages (at least not near enough to hold my interest). There are also speed bumps along the way that tends to toss me out </span>
  <span id="freeText7087005253423983546" style="display:none">DNF This is a great book, just not for me. The author is brilliant in her craft. As I have said before I am big on the Fictive Dream, have to have it. This book is a study in character. There is so much “telling” about the characters that the narrative overpowers the forward motion of the story. There isn’t any forward motion of the story that I could see in the first hundred pages (at least not near enough to hold my interest). There are also speed bumps along the way that tends to toss me out of the long telling narratives, and that is shifting points of view. For me this is the kind of book that can’t get out of the way of itself enough to tell the story (show the story). I will definitely take a peek at the author’s next book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7087005253423983546" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
